*We will be forming each part of the IP-address iteratively.*
``` java []
class Solution {
    public List<String> restoreIpAddresses(String s) {
        List<String> ans = new ArrayList<>();
        if (s.length() > 12) {      // max length can be 3 x 4 = 12
            return ans;
        }

        int len = s.length();
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(); // to store one address
        // length of each part can be min 1 and at max 3 
        // so we will one by one try with each length for first 3 parts
        for (int l1 = 1; l1 <= 3; l1++) {
            for (int l2 = 1; l2 <= 3; l2++) {
                for (int l3 = 1; l3 <= 3; l3++) {
                    // get the length for the 4th part
                    int l4 = len - l1 - l2 - l3;
                    // again, the 4th part should be of size 1-3
                    if (l4 > 0 && l4 <= 3) {    // if it is
                        // get the numbers from the partitioned strings
                        int p1 = getNum(s, 0, l1);
                        int p2 = getNum(s, l1, l1 + l2);
                        int p3 = getNum(s, l1 + l2, l1 + l2 + l3);
                        int p4 = getNum(s, l1 + l2 + l3, l1 + l2 + l3 + l4);
                        // if each of them is lesser than 255
                        // we can make it a candidate ip address
                        if (p1 <= 255 && p2 <= 255 && p3 <= 255 && p4 <= 255) {
                            sb.append(p1).append(".").append(p2).append(".")
                            .append(p3).append(".").append(p4);

                            // IMPORTANT:
                            // We need to avoid leading zeros
                            // if in the string if we have "025", 
                            // parseInt would convert it to 25
                            // so we will get a difference in the lengths
                            // otherwise length of our address should always be 3 + string's length
                            // the +3 is because of the 3 "." (dots) that we have added
                            if (sb.length() == len + 3) {   // if that's so
                                ans.add(sb.toString());     // add the IP to the ans list
                            }
                            // empty the stringbuilder coz we will create a new IP now
                            sb = new StringBuilder();
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }

    // this method returns the numeric value of the part of the string
    // we chose to make the method separate to avoid typing the same long thing again and again
    private int getNum(String s, int i, int j) {
        return Integer.parseInt(s.substring(i, j));
    }
}
```
---
#### Time complexity: 
- We are using `3` loops which would run `3 x 3 x 3` times.
- Inside that we are performing `substring()` operation `4` times on a string which can be at max `12` in length.
- So time complexity becomes $$O(3 * 3 * 3 * 4 * 12) => O(432)$$ in worst case which is constant in nature.

So we can say our time complexity is $$O(1)$$.

---
#### Space complexity:
We are using a stringbuilder who will store a string of size `12 + 3 = 15` at max which is again constant in nature.
So we can say our space coplexity is $$O(1)$$.

