solutions.content:
Nice problem which is a variant of more common combinatorics problems, but, as such, offers room for the same kind of approach to tackle it: a good old backtracking DFS across all the branches of our decision tree.

It would be tempting to try and move the `3` dots we have to consider creating a lot of substrings here and there, but that would not be too convenient, considering how many times we might be doing the same work over and over again, while progressing with partial strings we have already validated (and only once) is probably a much better approach.

And to do so, we will need a few variables, all at class level:
* `res` will be our accumulator variable, storing the valid permutations we will find for the provided digits;
* `s` will store our initial string at class level, `tmp` our temporary one (as mentioned above to proceed incrementally with already validated string chunks);
* `len` will store the length of our initial input;
* `digitsLeft` will keep track of how many digits we still need to add in our current `tmp` iteration, initially set to `4`.

In our main function, we will first of all give a proper value to `len`, then check if it is a value worth checking: any string outside of the `4 - 12` range would of course not work for us, providing either too few or too many digits for us to parse.

If we are still in, then we can assign a proper value to `s` and launch our `dfs` helper to compute all the possible permutations.

This helper function will take only one parameter (since I prefer keep as much as possible at class level, instead of passing copies or references of any information at class level), `start`, telling us from which character in `s` we start parsing; we will then:
* check if we reached an end case - ie: we are done adding digits to `tmp` (`digitsLeft == 0`), in which case:
	* if we know we exactly finished parsing the string (`start == len`) we also know we are checking a valid string, so we can append it to `res`;
	* in any case, we stop recursing with a `return` statement;
* if we are in the general case, we need to then consider three possible scenarios:
	* we can add `1` digit to `tmp`, which is always a valid scenario (I still left a conditional as a placeholder, in order to further optimise that on later iterations and, in any case, more easily tell the decision block apart):
		* we will decrease `digitsLeft`;
		* add `s[start]` to `tmp`;
		* add `'.'` to `tmp` if we still have `digitsLeft` to add later;
		* recursively call `dfs` with `start + 1`;
		* backtrack on both `tmp and `digitsLeft`;
	* we can add `2` digits to `tmp`, provided we have enough characters left and the first one is not `'0'` (no leading zeroes allowed!):
		* we will decrease `digitsLeft`;
		* add `s[start]` to `tmp`;
		* add `s[start + 1]` to `tmp`;
		* add `'.'` to `tmp` if we still have `digitsLeft` to add later;
		* recursively call `dfs` with `start + 2`;
		* backtrack on both `tmp and `digitsLeft`;
	* we can add `3` digits to `tmp`, provided we have enough characters left and the first one is `'1'` followed by any number of `'2'` followed by any number `< '4'` or followed by `'5'` in turn: by any third digits `< '6'`:
		* we will decrease `digitsLeft`;
		* add `s[start]` to `tmp`;
		* add `s[start + 1]` to `tmp`;
		* add `s[start + 2]` to `tmp`;
		* add `'.'` to `tmp` if we still have `digitsLeft` to add later;
		* recursively call `dfs` with `start + 2`;
		* backtrack on both `tmp and `digitsLeft`.

Once done, we can just `return` `res` and be done with it :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
    vector<string> res;
    string s, tmp;
    int len, digitsLeft = 4;
    void dfs(int start = 0) {
        // end case - no more digits to add
        if (!digitsLeft) {
            // if we are exactly at the end, we know it is a valid match
            if (start == len) res.push_back(tmp);
            return;
        }
        // general case
        // 1 digit addition
        if (true) {
            // updating digitsLeft and tmp
            digitsLeft--;
            tmp += s[start];
            if (digitsLeft) tmp += '.';
            dfs(start + 1);
            // backtracking digitsLeft and tmp
            tmp.resize(tmp.size() - 1 - (bool)digitsLeft);
            digitsLeft++;
        }
        // 2 digits addition
        if (s[start] != '0' && start < len - 1) {
            // updating digitsLeft and tmp
            digitsLeft--;
            tmp += s[start];
            tmp += s[start + 1];
            if (digitsLeft) tmp += '.';
            dfs(start + 2);
            // backtracking digitsLeft and tmp
            tmp.resize(tmp.size() - 2 - (bool)digitsLeft);
            digitsLeft++;
        }
        // 3 digits addition
        if ((s[start] == '1' || s[start] == '2' && (s[start + 1] < '5' || s[start + 1] == '5' && s[start + 2] < '6')) && start < len - 2) {
            // updating digitsLeft and tmp
            digitsLeft--;
            tmp += s[start];
            tmp += s[start + 1];
            tmp += s[start + 2];
            if (digitsLeft) tmp += '.';
            dfs(start + 3);
            // backtracking digitsLeft and tmp
            tmp.resize(tmp.size() - 3 - (bool)digitsLeft);
            digitsLeft++;
        }
    }
public:
    vector<string> restoreIpAddresses(string s) {
        len = s.size();
        if (len < 4 || len > 12) return res;
        this->s = s;
        dfs();
        return res;
    }
};
```

Hey, we are adding and removing a lot of characters in our three cases, arent't we? Well, it turns out that the third case will be valid only if the first two digits are in the valid range and the first to digits are in the valid range when the first one is (which happens always), so we can avoid a bit of repeated code, manage `digitsLeft` only once and streamline our construction of `tmp` a bit more efficiently and in a DRYer fashion, like this:

```cpp
class Solution {
    vector<string> res;
    string s, tmp;
    int len, digitsLeft = 4;
    void dfs(int start = 0) {
        // end case - no more digits to add
        if (!digitsLeft) {
            // if we are exactly at the end, we know it is a valid match
            if (start == len) res.push_back(tmp);
            return;
        }
        // support variables
        int tmpStartLen = tmp.size();
        // general cases:
        // updating digitsLeft and tmp
        digitsLeft--;
        tmp += s[start];
        // 1 digit addition
        if (true) {
            // updating tmp and recursing
            if (digitsLeft) tmp += '.';
            dfs(start + 1);
            // backtracking the dot
            if (digitsLeft) tmp.pop_back();
        }
        // 2 digits addition
        if (s[start] != '0' && start < len - 1) {
            // updating tmp and recursing
            tmp += s[start + 1];
            if (digitsLeft) tmp += '.';
            dfs(start + 2);
            // backtracking the dot
            if (digitsLeft) tmp.pop_back();
        }
        // 3 digits addition
        if ((s[start] == '1' || s[start] == '2' && (s[start + 1] < '5' || s[start + 1] == '5' && s[start + 2] < '6')) && start < len - 2) {
            // updating tmp and recursing
            tmp += s[start + 2];
            if (digitsLeft) tmp += '.';
            dfs(start + 3);
        }
        // backtracking digitsLeft and tmp
        tmp.resize(tmpStartLen);
        digitsLeft++;
    }
public:
    vector<string> restoreIpAddresses(string s) {
        // updating len and checking if we can proceed or not
        len = s.size();
        if (len < 4 || len > 12) return res;
        // updating s and generating the results
        this->s = s;
        dfs();
        return res;
    }
};
```

Now, remember that placeholder conditional I put before the first block for adding one digit to `tmp`?

I wanted to optimise it so that it would give us only calls when we have enough characters left to recurse; for example, if our initial string is `"255255255255"`, there is clearly no point in taking only `'2`', since we cannot make `3` other valid digits with the left over (`"55255255255"`); it turns out it works wonders, since I tried for example without these conditionals the previous code for `"25525511135"` would have `71` recursive calls; with my code, it is now only `9`😎!

We will also need to update `tmp` regardless at each step, since we might have some cases in which the second digit is not enough, but the third is okay or the like; but it works wonders in this new version:

```cpp
class Solution {
    vector<string> res;
    string s, tmp;
    int len, digitsLeft = 4;
    void dfs(int start = 0) {
        // end case - no more digits to add
        if (!digitsLeft) {
            // if we are exactly at the end, we know it is a valid match
            if (start == len) res.push_back(tmp);
            return;
        }
        // support variables
        int tmpStartLen = tmp.size(), charsLeft = len - start, lmtL, lmtR;
        // general cases:
        // updating digitsLeft and tmp
        digitsLeft--;
        lmtL = 1 * digitsLeft, lmtR = 3 * lmtL;
        tmp += s[start];
        // 1 digit addition
        if (--charsLeft >= lmtL && charsLeft <= lmtR) {
            // updating tmp and recursing
            if (digitsLeft) tmp += '.';
            dfs(start + 1);
            // backtracking the dot
            if (digitsLeft) tmp.pop_back();
        }
        tmp += s[start + 1];
        // 2 digits addition
        if (s[start] != '0' && --charsLeft >= lmtL && charsLeft <= lmtR) {
            // updating tmp and recursing
            if (digitsLeft) tmp += '.';
            dfs(start + 2);
            // backtracking the dot
            if (digitsLeft) tmp.pop_back();
        }
        // 3 digits addition
        tmp += s[start + 2];
        if ((s[start] == '1' || s[start] == '2' && (s[start + 1] < '5' || s[start + 1] == '5' && s[start + 2] < '6')) && --charsLeft >= lmtL && charsLeft <= lmtR) {
            // updating tmp and recursing
            if (digitsLeft) tmp += '.';
            dfs(start + 3);
        }
        // backtracking digitsLeft and tmp
        tmp.resize(tmpStartLen);
        digitsLeft++;
    }
public:
    vector<string> restoreIpAddresses(string s) {
        // updating len and checking if we can proceed or not
        len = s.size();
        if (len < 4 || len > 12) return res;
        // updating s and generating the results
        this->s = s;
        dfs();
        return res;
    }
};
```

The last tiny bit of optimisation, to avoid reallocations, will be to set `res` initially always to get the maximum capacity of `19` (the longest possible series of permutations we might have for a string like `"11111111"`) and then resize accordingly, to avoid reallocations - it saves a bit of memory, it seems, but not as much as cutting on the needless recursions:

```cpp
class Solution {
    vector<string> res;
    string s, tmp;
    int len, digitsLeft = 4, w = 0;
    void dfs(int start = 0) {
        // end case - no more digits to add
        if (!digitsLeft) {
            // if we are exactly at the end, we know it is a valid match
            if (start == len) res[w++] = tmp;
            return;
        }
        // support variables
        int tmpStartLen = tmp.size(), charsLeft = len - start, lmtL, lmtR;
        // general cases:
        // updating digitsLeft and tmp
        digitsLeft--;
        lmtL = 1 * digitsLeft, lmtR = 3 * lmtL;
        tmp += s[start];
        // 1 digit addition
        if (--charsLeft >= lmtL && charsLeft <= lmtR) {
            // updating tmp and recursing
            if (digitsLeft) tmp += '.';
            dfs(start + 1);
            // backtracking the dot
            if (digitsLeft) tmp.pop_back();
        }
        tmp += s[start + 1];
        // 2 digits addition
        if (s[start] != '0' && --charsLeft >= lmtL && charsLeft <= lmtR) {
            // updating tmp and recursing
            if (digitsLeft) tmp += '.';
            dfs(start + 2);
            // backtracking the dot
            if (digitsLeft) tmp.pop_back();
        }
        // 3 digits addition
        tmp += s[start + 2];
        if ((s[start] == '1' || s[start] == '2' && (s[start + 1] < '5' || s[start + 1] == '5' && s[start + 2] < '6')) && --charsLeft >= lmtL && charsLeft <= lmtR) {
            // updating tmp and recursing
            if (digitsLeft) tmp += '.';
            dfs(start + 3);
        }
        // backtracking digitsLeft and tmp
        tmp.resize(tmpStartLen);
        digitsLeft++;
    }
public:
    vector<string> restoreIpAddresses(string s) {
        // updating len and checking if we can proceed or not
        len = s.size();
        if (len < 4 || len > 12) return res;
        // updating s and generating the results
        this->s = s;
        res.resize(19);
        dfs();
        res.resize(w);
        return res;
    }
};
```

