After reading this solution, many of you might tag this problem as easy and not medium
Do let me know in comments if you guys find it difficult to understand some point, will keep those points in mind for future posts

Let me first repost the desired part of question here :)

This is how the UTF-8 encoding would work:

```
 Number of Bytes   |        UTF-8 Octet Sequence
                       |              (binary)
   --------------------+-----------------------------------------
            1          |   0xxxxxxx
            2          |   110xxxxx 10xxxxxx
            3          |   1110xxxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx
            4          |   11110xxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx 10xxxxxx
```

So, a UTF-8 can have 1 to 4 byes

Lets break down the problem
0. We cannot have more than 4 bytes in UTF-8
1. To check the number of bytes i.e. 1,2,3,4 or something else
2. Now the next n-1 numbers should have 10 in their most significant bit
3. One more point, will cover later ;)
4. Lets bring it all togeather

Let me take both parts one by one

**1. To check the number of bytes i.e. 1,2,3,4 or something else**

Let me create a method getNumberOfBytes, which takes an integer number as input and tell me the number of bytes in this sequence

```
 public int getNumberOfBytes(int data){
        //If it starts with 0 then, right shifting it by 7 times gives 0
        if((data>>7)==0) return 1;
        //If it starts with 110, then right shifting by 5 times gives 110 i.e. 6
        if((data>>5)==6) return 2;
        //If it starts with 1110, then right shifting by 4 times gives 1110 i.e. 14
        if((data>>4)==14) return 3;
        //If it starts with 11110, then right shifting by 3 times gives 11110 i.e. 30
        if((data>>3)==30) return 4;
        else return -1;
    }
```

**2. Now the next n-1 numbers should have 10 in their most significant bit**
This will check, if the number actually has 10 in its MSB.
This will be called for the next n-1 numbers'
```
//To check if number actually starts with 10
    public boolean isTrailingNumber(int data){
        //If it starts with 10, then right shifting by 6 times gives 10 i.e. 2
        return ((data>>6)==2);
    }
```

**3. One more point, will cover later ;)**
Now, we find out the number of bits in point 1, and for remaining n-1 elements we checked if they are having 10 in their MSB.
What if we get number of bytes as n, but we dont have n numbes after that ?
So, its better if after getting the number of bytes we also check if we have n-1 numbers after it. This will save our bit operation for trailing numbers

**4. Lets bring it all togeather**
Now, lets write our parent code which uses the code written in 1 & 2 plus some more logic :)

I will be using a pointer technique here to iterate over array.

```
public boolean validUtf8(int[] data) {
        //Initialize pointer to 0
        int p=0;
        //Run a loop till pointer reaches the end
        while(p<data.length){
            //Get the number of bytes for the data
            int numberOfBytes = getNumberOfBytes(data[p]);
            //If number of bytes is not 1,2,3 or 4 or something else, we will return false
            if(numberOfBytes==-1) return false;
            //To check if we have n-1 number after this point
            if(numberOfBytes>data.length-p) return false;
            //Increment the pointer for next iteration
            p++;
            //Now if we have numberOfBytes more than 1, we need to check that next n-1 numbers should start with 10 in MSB
            while (numberOfBytes>1){
                //Using the numberOfBytes as the counter itself
                numberOfBytes--;
                //If this number doesn't starts with 10, we can return false from here
                if(!isTrailingNumber(data[p]))
                    return false;
                //Increment the main pointer so we dont process this entry again :)
                p++;
            }
        }
        //If everything goes right, we will land here :)
        return true;
    }

```
