This problem ask for *A[i] > 2A[j] with i < j*. 
**1. Fix j, that is to find the number of elements > 2A[j] to its left. With Binary Index Tree, we scan from left.
2. Or fix i, *A[i] / 2 > A[j] with i < j*, find the number of elements < A[i] / 2 to its right. With Binary Index Tree, we scan from right.**

This is scanning from left becase we are looking for numbers that is > 2A[j] to its left.
```
public int reversePairs(int[] A) {
        int res = 0;
        int n = A.length;
        int[] copy = Arrays.copyOf(A, n);
        int[] bit = new int[n + 1];
        Arrays.sort(copy);

        for (int x: A) {
            res += getSum(bit, index2(copy, 2L * x)  + 1);// A[i] > 2 x for any i > index2(copy, 2L * x) in BIT
            update(bit, index2(copy, x), 1);
        }
        return res;
    }

 // helper function
    // binary search to find the last element that <= val in input array
    // input A should be sorted
    private int index2(int[] A, long val) {
        int left = 0, r = A.length;

        while (left < r) {
        	int m = left + ((r - left) >> 1);

        	if (A[m] > val) {
        	    r = m; // m - 1 must be the position, since BIT starts from 1, return r
        	} else {
        	    left = m + 1;
        	}
        }
        return r;// r is the final index in BIT
    }

	// Binary Index Tree
    // O(logn)
    // @bit : binary index tree array
    // @i : from start index to index i in bit (inclusively)
    // return : the prefix sum from start index to index i
    private int getSum(int[] bit, int i) {
        int sum = 0;
        while (i < bit.length) {
            sum += bit[i];
            i = i + (i & -i);
        }
        return sum;
    }

    // O(logn)
    // update the value in index i by diff
    private void update(int[] bit, int i, int diff) {
        // need to update all of its affected nodes as well
        while (i > 0) {
            bit[i] += diff;
            i = i - (i & -i);
        }
    }
```

This is scanning from right becase we are looking for numbers that is > A[i] / 2to its right.
